            <h3>Flushdyke - a victim of progress: sketches by Douglas Brammer </h3>
            <p align="justify">The unique sketches and drawing presented here are part of a series done by Douglas Brammer, which he calls <em>&quot;Flushdyke - a Victim of Progress: 1940 - 1960&quot;</em>. All the drawings are done from Douglas' phenomenal memory and show many buildings that have long since disappeared. It is a pictorial essay of a community now decimated by massive industrial development, which has seen Flushdyke change from a thriving village suburb of Ossett to a sprawling industrial estate, extending to both sides of the A638 main thoroughfare. </p>
            <p align="center"><strong> Click on any of the pictures below for a larger, colour version, which will open in a new window. </strong></p>
            <p align="center"><a href="pages/flushdyke_wakefield_road.html" target="_blank"><img src="images/flushdyke_wakefield_rd_small.jpg" alt="Wakefield Road, Flushdyke" width="498" height="359" border="0"></a></p>
            <p align="left"><strong>Above:</strong> Wakefield Road, Flushdyke with Lodge Hill Farm in the background (Map 1). </p>
            <p align="justify">Douglas says this of his drawings:</p>
            <blockquote>
              <p align="justify"><em>&quot;When I realised that there were hardly any recorded photographs of Flushdyke, where I had grown up, I tried to visualise certain buildings and places. Workhouse Yard was one place I felt ought to be recorded because of its antiquity and history. My father who was born at Spring Mill and who had lived in Workhouse Yard had no photographs, although he was an avid collector of images of the places that he had visited.</em></p>
              <p align="justify"><em>I sketched the Workhouse Yard from memory and all the other extinct buildings followed. I know that I am not fully accurate in many things I've drawn and it is how I remember it. However, I am keen to hear other people's memories or obtain any photographs of &quot;lost&quot; Flushdyke.&quot;</em></p>
            </blockquote>
            <p align="justify">Douglas has prepared a map of the Flushdyke area and if you click on the smaller black and white image presented below, a larger colour map will be displayed with some more information about the local community. </p>
            <p align="center"><a href="pages/flushdyke_map.html" target="_blank"><img src="images/flushdyke_map_key_small.jpg" alt="Flushdyke Map" width="500" height="349" border="0"></a></p>
            <p align="left"><strong>Above:</strong> Flushdyke Map by Douglas Brammer showing the village before it became industrialised. </p>
            <p align="center"><a href="images/flushdyke_map_1771.jpg" target="_blank"><img src="images/flushdyke_map_1771_small.jpg" alt="Flushdyke in 1771" width="501" height="375" border="0"></a></p>
            <p align="left"><strong>Above:</strong> Although not part of Douglas Brammer's collection, this extremely rare 1771 map of Flushdyke, Ossett (kindly provided by Alan Howe) was drawn up to support a legal dispute between Joshua Haigh, who lived at Longlands House and Joseph Ingham. If you click on the map above, a larger and hopefully more readable version will open in a new window. </p>
            <p align="center"><a href="pages/flushdyke_commercial_hotel.html" target="_blank"><img src="images/flushdyke_commercial_hotel_small.jpg" alt="Commercial Hotel, Dewsbury Road, Flushdyke " width="498" height="318" border="0"></a></p>
            <p align="left"><strong>Above:</strong> The Commercial Hotel at the bottom of Dale Street on Dewsbury Road (Map 2).</p>
            <p align="center"><a href="pages/flushdyke_dale_street_end.html" target="_blank"><img src="images/flushdyke_towards_dale_street_small.jpg" alt="Flushdyke, looking towards Dale Street" width="357" height="499" border="0"></a></p>
            <p align="left"><strong>Above:</strong> Flushdyke, Ossett looking towards Dale Street (Map 3)</p>
            <p align="center"><a href="pages/flushdyke_dale_street_junction.html" target="_blank"><img src="images/flushdyke_dale_street_end_small.jpg" alt="Junction of Dale Street and Wakefield Rd, Flushdyke" width="500" height="350" border="0"></a>. </p>
            <p align="left"><strong>Above:</strong> Junction of Dale Street with Wakefield Road, Flushdyke (Map 4).</p>
            <p align="center"><a href="pages/flushdyke_mitchells.html" target="_blank"><img src="images/flushdyke_vets_small.jpg" alt="Flushdyke Vet's Surgery" width="498" height="340" border="0"></a></p>
            <p align="left"><strong>Above: </strong>Old house now used as a vet's surgery along Dewsbury Road in Flushdyke, Ossett (Map 5). </p>
            <p align="center"><a href="pages/flushdyke_vironita.html" target="_blank"><img src="images/flushdyke_vironita_small.jpg" alt="Vironita Health Drink factory in Flushdyke" width="499" height="363" border="0"></a></p>
            <p align="left"><strong>Above:</strong> Vironita health drink factory, (formerly Riley's Fireworks) located Dewsbury Road, Flushdyke circa 1940s (Map 6). </p>
            <p align="center"><a href="pages/flushdyke_fern_house.html" target="_blank"><img src="images/flushdyke_fern_house_small.jpg" alt="Fern House" width="499" height="365" border="0"></a> </p>
            <p align="left"><strong>Above:</strong> Fern House Working Men's Club. circa 1950 with the old Ossett Town football ground immediately behind (Map 7). </p>
            <p align="center"><a href="pages/flushdyke_tommy_brooks_farm.html" target="_blank"><img src="images/flushdyke_arp_shelter_small.jpg" alt="WW2 ARP Shelter, Flushdyke " width="500" height="368" border="0"></a></p>
            <p align="left"><strong>Above:</strong> WW2 air raid shelter at Tommy Brooke's farm along Dewsbury Road in Flushdyke (Map 8). </p>
            <p align="center"><a href="pages/flushdyke_wainwrights.html" target="_blank"><img src="images/flushdyke_wainwright_small.jpg" alt="Wainwright's Shop, Flushdyke" width="498" height="364" border="0"></a></p>
            <p align="left"><strong>Above:</strong> Wainwright's electrical shop, which specialised in batteries for radios, before mains electricity was available in Ossett (Map 9).</p>
            <p align="center"><a href="pages/flushdyke_sandbed.html" target="_blank"><img src="images/flushdyke_sandbed_terrace_small.jpg" alt="Sandbed Terrace, Flushdyke" width="370" height="499" border="0"></a></p>
            <p align="left"><strong>Above: </strong>Sandbed Terrace, Flushdyke (Map 10). </p>
            <p align="center"><a href="pages/flushdyke_bickles.html" target="_blank"><img src="images/flushdyke_bickles_grocers_small.jpg" alt="Bickles Grocers, Flushdyke, Ossett" width="498" height="355" border="0"></a></p>
            <p align="left"><strong>Above:</strong> J. Bickle, Grocer's Shop, Flushdyke, Ossett (Map 11).</p>
            <p align="center"><a href="pages/flushdyke_eldon_terrace.html" target="_blank"><img src="images/flushdyke_eldon_terrace_small.jpg" alt="Eldon Terrace, Flushdyke" width="499" height="357" border="0"></a></p>
            <p align="left"><strong>Above:</strong> Eldon Terrace, Flushdyke circa 1945 (Map 12). </p>
            <p align="center"><a href="pages/flushdyke_st_oswalds.html" target="_blank"><img src="images/flushdyke_st_oswalds_mission_small.jpg" alt="St. Oswald's Mission, Flushdyke" width="499" height="363" border="0"></a></p>
            <p align="left"><strong>Above:</strong> St. Oswald's Mission, Flushdyke (Map 13).</p>
            <p align="center"><a href="pages/flushdyke_workhouse.html" target="_blank"><img src="images/flushdyke_workhouse_yard_small.jpg" alt="Workhouse Yard, Flushdyke" width="500" height="368" border="0"></a></p>
            <p align="justify"><strong>Above:</strong> Workhouse Yard, Flushdyke circa 1945 (Map 14).</p>
            <p align="center"><a href="pages/flushdyke_coal_delivery.html" target="_blank"><img src="images/flushdyke_coal_delivery_small.jpg" alt="Coal delivery at Flushdyke 1940s" width="500" height="350" border="0"></a></p>
            <p align="left"><strong>Above:</strong> Delivery of coal by horse and cart at Flushdyke in the 1940s (Map 15).</p>
            <p align="center"><a href="pages/flushdyke_almshouses.html" target="_blank"><img src="images/flushdyke_almshouses_small.jpg" alt="Flushdyke Almshouses" width="498" height="363" border="0"></a></p>
            <p align="left"><strong>Above: </strong>The old almshouses at Flushdyke with the 'Flushdyke Flyer' coach picking up passengers in the 1950s (Map 16).</p>
            <p align="center"><a href="pages/flushdyke_co-op.html" target="_blank"><img src="images/flushdyke_coop_small.jpg" alt="Flushdyke Co-op" width="498" height="363" border="0"></a></p>
            <p align="left"><strong>Above:</strong> Flushdyke Co-operative store and the rag warehouse of Frank North (Map 17). </p>
            <p align="center"><a href="pages/flushdyke_gothards.html" target="_blank"><img src="images/flushdyke_gothards_stable_small.jpg" alt="Gothard's Stables, Flushdyke" width="498" height="357" border="0"></a></p>
            <p align="left"><strong>Above:</strong> Gothard's Stables Flushdyke, Ossett (Map 18). </p>
            <p align="center"><a href="pages/flushdyke_kidgers.html" target="_blank"><img src="images/flushdyke_kidgers_shop_small.jpg" alt="Kidger's Shop, Flushdyke" width="498" height="364" border="0"></a></p>
            <p align="left"><strong>Above:</strong> Kidger's shoe repair shop, Flushdyke (Map 19) </p>
            <p align="center"><a href="pages/flushdyke_railway_bridge.html" target="_blank"><img src="images/flushdyke_railway_bridge_small.jpg" alt="Flushdyke Railway Bridge" width="498" height="362" border="0"></a></p>
            <p align="left"><strong>Above:</strong> Flushdyke railway bridge, now demolished (Map 20). </p>
            <p align="center"><a href="pages/flushdyke_railway_hotel.html" target="_blank"><img src="images/flushdyke_railway_hotel_small.jpg" alt="Railway Hotel and the Diggings" width="361" height="497" border="0"></a></p>
            <p align="left"><strong>Above:</strong> Railway Hotel and a terrace of houses called the Diggings, which were set down some six feet from the roadside (Map 21). </p>
            <p align="center"><a href="pages/flushdyke_spencers.html" target="_blank"><img src="images/flushdyke_spencer_and_halstead_small.jpg" alt="Spencer &amp; Halstead" width="498" height="359" border="0"></a></p>
            <p align="left"><strong>Above:</strong> Ashton's Buildings with the Spencer &amp; Halstead engineering works behind, Flushdyke (Map 22).</p>
            <p align="center"><a href="pages/flushdyke_fisheries.html" target="_blank"><img src="images/flushdyke_fisheries_small.jpg" alt="Flushdyke Fish &amp; Chip  Shop" width="498" height="365" border="0"></a> </p>
            <p align="left"><strong>Above:</strong> Flushdyke Fisheries in the 1940s (Map 23). </p>
            <p align="center"><a href="pages/flushdyke_school.html" target="_blank"><img src="images/flushdyke_school_small.jpg" alt="Flushdyke School from Shepherd Hill" width="499" height="351" border="0"></a></p>
